Since 1956, the PTA participated substantially in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later built an improved version, the RM-1A, and in 1959 began in the Błędów desert of flight tests with the Zweistufenrakete RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and are used for the observation of altitude.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
Successor of the first rockets of the type RM was the Meteor-1 rocket developed in the years from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as Zweistufenrakete, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed by this missile (Meteor-1A, - 1B and - 1C), that the size of the space for scientific instruments differed from each other.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport capacity with 0.4 liters, Meteor-1 (B) 0.34 liters and Meteor-1 C over 0.62 l.
The maximum flight altitude was in all three types of 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed in the Aviation Institute, whose initial flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a takeoff weight of 380 kg, and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 miles.
Then the versions were Meteor-2 H and Meteor-3.
Worth mentioning is also the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for space research) followed in the year 1960, on the two years later the establishment of a National Committee of COSPAR.
Poland participated in the INTERCOSMOS programme to space exploration with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski, Vladimír Remek was second inter Cosmonaut after the Czechs.
